- She's scared, I think.
- I know. She doesn't know where to go.

00:47.100 --> 00:51.333
♪♪

01:10.000 --> 01:12.000
- Do we have any
we're not feeding?

01:12.000 --> 01:13.000
- No.

01:18.300 --> 01:23.333
♪♪

01:26.333 --> 01:27.333
- Here you go.

01:28.700 --> 01:32.000
Mona, there you go,
girly.

01:32.000 --> 01:33.000
It's okay.

01:33.667 --> 01:34.700
Rowdy's not eating,

01:34.700 --> 01:36.633
and Dominique's being
real picky.

01:36.633 --> 01:41.000
♪♪

01:47.467 --> 01:48.467
Hey, guys.

02:13.600 --> 02:15.000
Okay, little ones.

02:18.000 --> 02:19.600
You were the hungriest.

02:19.600 --> 02:24.000
♪♪

02:24.000 --> 02:25.000
All right.

02:27.333 --> 02:29.333
Humphrey, you settle down,
man.

02:29.333 --> 02:32.000
Hey, Maisie.
You silly girl.

02:32.700 --> 02:34.567
- Good morning, Amelia.

02:34.567 --> 02:35.567
There's your food.

02:39.600 --> 02:40.600
- Come on, Gus!

02:42.500 --> 02:44.500
Come on, Tito.
Are you coming?

02:44.500 --> 02:45.433
Good boy.

02:46.200 --> 02:49.200
I know! I know!
I know, come on.

02:50.333 --> 02:52.067
What? You sleeping in this morning?

02:53.333 --> 02:54.333
You sleeping in?

02:58.667 --> 03:02.500
♪♪

03:33.467 --> 03:35.467
Amelia, stop that.

03:37.633 --> 03:39.600
What, Tito?
What, Tito?

03:39.600 --> 03:42.300
When we started rescuing dogs
15 years ago,

03:42.300 --> 03:46.467
I never dreamed
we would have a real rescue.

03:46.467 --> 03:49.333
And I never dreamed we would
have a rescue this size

03:49.333 --> 03:53.767
that has taken over, you know,
our whole home, our lives.

03:55.100 --> 03:56.500
Okay.

03:58.100 --> 03:59.167
Oh, hush.

03:59.167 --> 04:02.167
Dominique.
Dominique, come on.

04:02.167 --> 04:05.133
<i>We have 71 dogs in the house currently,</i>

04:05.133 --> 04:10.200
<i>and I don't really know</i>
<i>of any other rescues</i>

04:10.200 --> 04:13.633
<i>that just let dogs live</i>
<i>in their house like we do.</i>

04:15.200 --> 04:17.166
Want me to bring you lunch,
old guy?

04:17.166 --> 04:19.399
Most people who rescue dogs

04:19.399 --> 04:22.333
have kennels separate
from their houses,

04:22.333 --> 04:24.533
but we'd saved so many animals

04:24.533 --> 04:28.267
that had been victimized
or injured.

04:28.267 --> 04:31.333
And we don't always know what
we're getting into with that.

04:31.333 --> 04:34.167
And that's why living with them
sometimes is so important

04:34.167 --> 04:36.667
'cause we really find out
what we need to know

04:36.667 --> 04:39.100
before they get adopted
by someone.

04:39.100 --> 04:41.333
What happens sometimes is--
yes, it is.

04:41.333 --> 04:43.267
We've told you
this story before.

04:43.267 --> 04:45.367
We've told you a lot.

04:45.367 --> 04:49.600
She was going stir-crazy being
in the shelter for too long.

04:49.600 --> 04:51.267
We'd have felt terrible
if we made her stay

04:51.267 --> 04:53.700
in the wrong conditions
for another week, even.

04:53.700 --> 04:56.267
So, it's gonna work out
for this sweetheart,

04:56.267 --> 04:58.233
I can promise you that.

04:58.233 --> 05:00.300
I remember how excited when we hit

05:00.300 --> 05:02.267
the 1,000th adoption.

05:02.267 --> 05:04.600
Danny and I thought
we hit the lottery, you know?

05:04.600 --> 05:06.533
We were like, "Can you believe
we made it to a thousand?"

05:06.533 --> 05:07.667
Okay, family walk...

05:07.667 --> 05:09.200
And right now, I mean,

05:09.200 --> 05:11.133
we're only a hundred
and a few dogs away

05:11.133 --> 05:13.067
from hitting
the 10,000th adoption.

05:13.067 --> 05:15.133
Let's go.
Come on.

05:15.133 --> 05:18.133
- Boys, come on.
- Come on. Come on.

05:22.500 --> 05:25.633
Hi, guys. Hi.

05:25.633 --> 05:27.533
How are you guys, huh?

05:27.533 --> 05:28.533
Doggies.

05:29.767 --> 05:30.767
Doggies, hi.

05:35.533 --> 05:40.367
<i>We get the majority of our</i>
<i>dogs from animal shelters.</i>

05:40.367 --> 05:43.467
<i>A lot of the shelters have</i>

05:43.467 --> 05:46.733
<i>what they call "red code day,"</i>
<i>which is euthanasia day.</i>

05:46.733 --> 05:50.600
<i>Sometimes I can get 100 e-mails</i>
<i>from 20 shelters</i>

05:50.600 --> 05:54.067
asking us to take dogs off
their euthanasia list.

05:54.067 --> 05:58.400
This is just one normal e-mail
from one shelter.

05:58.400 --> 06:00.633
These are all,
as you can see, it says,

06:00.633 --> 06:03.233
"final date," "expired,"
"critical."

06:03.233 --> 06:08.333
So these animals are about
to be euthanized today.

06:08.333 --> 06:10.367
Over 4 million animals
are euthanized

06:10.367 --> 06:12.267
every year in America.

06:12.267 --> 06:14.133
It's very, very sad.

06:14.133 --> 06:17.267
You look at their faces,
you look at their eyes,

06:17.267 --> 06:20.267
and they're just begging
for someone to save 'em.

06:40.533 --> 06:42.533
Hello.

06:42.533 --> 06:44.300
That's a pretty color.

06:44.300 --> 06:46.367
Yeah, she's beautiful.

06:51.133 --> 06:53.700
This little guy here.

06:53.700 --> 06:55.633
That's the one
we're checking on.

06:55.633 --> 06:58.033
She's very sweet.
Housebroken.

06:58.033 --> 07:02.033
A lady got her off Facebook
and she didn't want her anymore.

07:02.033 --> 07:04.400
This one came from a hoarder
and he still needs some work.

07:04.400 --> 07:07.133
- Okay.
- They came in really, really, really, really shy.

07:07.133 --> 07:08.767
We've got three left.
They're probably

07:08.767 --> 07:11.767
the nicest-looking hoarding dogs
I've ever seen.

07:11.767 --> 07:13.667
- And there's Chester.
- You are cute.

07:13.667 --> 07:16.467
- He's a rat terrier mix.
- Hey, Chester. And how old is he?

07:16.467 --> 07:19.167
He's about four years old.
He came in as a stray.

07:19.167 --> 07:21.300
Is he pretty settled,
though, normally, or...?

07:21.300 --> 07:23.000
He usually is, yes.

07:23.000 --> 07:24.500
He's been outside,
so he's all hyped up.

07:24.500 --> 07:26.167
He's been runnin'
in the yard.

07:26.167 --> 07:30.000
<i>It's hard to pick up dogs that are on euthanasia</i>

07:30.000 --> 07:33.533
<i>because you already know</i>
<i>they don't really have a chance</i>

07:33.533 --> 07:35.600
<i>I will ask them if they can</i>
<i>give me any description</i>

07:35.600 --> 07:37.600
<i>on their personality, if they're friendly,</i>
<i>if they're aggressive,</i>

07:37.600 --> 07:39.533
<i>if they're dog-aggressive,</i>
<i>cat-aggressive.</i>

07:39.533 --> 07:42.233
<i>And, I mean, we don't want</i>
<i>to pick the perfect dog.</i>

07:42.233 --> 07:45.367
<i>We want to pick a dog that we can help and save and hopefully rehab.</i>

07:46.733 --> 07:49.000
As you can see,
this one is active.

07:49.000 --> 07:51.433
- And it's black, so it's gonna be kind of hard for us.
- Right, right.

07:51.433 --> 07:53.400
So, maybe,
maybe that would be one.

07:53.400 --> 07:56.000
We don't need another one that's hyper right now.

07:56.000 --> 07:58.000
We've got about four
of those.

07:58.000 --> 07:59.767
Let's look, now.

07:59.767 --> 08:02.333
<i>Shelters, by law,</i>

08:02.333 --> 08:05.433
<i>they have to take every animal</i>
<i>dropped off here.</i>

08:05.433 --> 08:11.367
We receive 5,000 animals a year
at our animal shelter.

08:11.367 --> 08:14.000
<i>We can hold 125.</i>

08:14.000 --> 08:18.267
<i>If we're overloaded,</i>
<i>then we have to make room.</i>

08:18.267 --> 08:22.233
He came in, in a trap,
through Animal Control.

08:22.233 --> 08:25.100
They'd said that he was mean
and vicious

08:25.100 --> 08:27.467
and to be careful 'cause
he would eat us for lunch.

08:27.467 --> 08:31.533
Well, ahem... here he is.
- Doesn't look it.

08:31.533 --> 08:36.200
<i>Seeing their faces and knowing</i>
<i>they're going to die...</i>

08:36.200 --> 08:40.700
<i>that drives me harder</i>
<i>to want to save more.</i>

08:40.700 --> 08:46.533
I don't think I could ever
turn my back on this

08:46.533 --> 08:48.333
'cause I couldn't live
with the guilt

08:48.333 --> 08:52.000
of walking away from all
those faces that need help.

08:52.000 --> 08:54.233
He needs a really good,
special home.

08:54.233 --> 08:57.033
- Someone that's gonna take care of him.
- Do you wanna go home, hmm?

08:57.033 --> 09:00.233
<i>It's a funny emotion because there's a part of me</i>

09:00.233 --> 09:03.067
<i>that would love</i>
<i>to be selfish and say,</i>

09:03.067 --> 09:05.533
"We've rescued
almost 10,000 dogs.

09:05.533 --> 09:07.600
"We're gonna go pick up.
We're gonna go travel.

09:07.600 --> 09:10.033
"We're gonna go live
the rest of our life

09:10.033 --> 09:12.267
and have a good life,"

09:12.267 --> 09:17.200
but my internal insides
won't let me do it.

09:19.367 --> 09:21.067
This is Apollo.

09:21.067 --> 09:23.300
He was runnin' on the side
of the road, stray.

09:23.300 --> 09:25.100
He's been very friendly.

09:25.100 --> 09:30.000
He was injured as a puppy,
um, so he does have a bum leg,

09:30.000 --> 09:33.000
so we've had no interest
in him whatsoever.

09:33.000 --> 09:35.100
Apollo, do you want
to go home, huh?

09:35.100 --> 09:37.733
You wanna go home
and get out of here?

09:37.733 --> 09:41.100
The ones that are very friendly,
very cute, furry,

09:41.100 --> 09:42.733
those get adopted immediately.

09:42.733 --> 09:45.067
What we usually try to do
is try to get a lot

09:45.067 --> 09:49.633
that are not very popular
to get adopted,

09:49.633 --> 09:52.167
so that they can get
a home.

09:52.167 --> 09:53.500
And that's Moose.

09:53.500 --> 09:55.533
We'll get you
ice creamies.

09:55.533 --> 09:57.667
- I think this dog has...
- Yeah, come on.

09:57.667 --> 10:00.300
...basset, Pekingese,
cocker spaniel...

10:00.300 --> 10:03.433
...golden retriever, setter...
- Come on.

10:03.433 --> 10:05.500
- Huh?
...and a little chow.

10:05.500 --> 10:08.167
Not to mention bloodhound
and Afghan and...

10:08.167 --> 10:10.133
- Well, look at the coat.
- That's beautiful.

10:10.133 --> 10:12.267
It's got the coat
of an Akita.

10:12.267 --> 10:13.633
Let's put Akita
in there, too.

10:13.633 --> 10:16.200
- Look at it.
- Oh, it's beautiful.

10:16.200 --> 10:17.567
You look like a loaf
of bread.

10:17.567 --> 10:19.333
Watch it-- watch it run
now. Come on, Moose.

10:19.333 --> 10:20.400
- It's just a rectangle.
- Moosey!

10:20.400 --> 10:23.100
Is that not the cutest thing you've ever seen in your life?
- That is precious.

10:23.100 --> 10:24.500
- It's not but eight weeks old.

10:24.500 --> 10:27.000
Moose!

10:27.000 --> 10:29.700
Looks like a cocktail table.

10:29.700 --> 10:31.200
<i>Not everyone's born</i>

10:31.200 --> 10:34.367
<i>with the very same gifts</i>
<i>and the same luck.</i>

10:34.367 --> 10:36.433
<i>Because of that,</i>
<i>they have to have</i>

10:36.433 --> 10:39.100
<i>a little extra help,</i>
<i>and I think that ideology</i>

10:39.100 --> 10:41.633
<i>has gone with me</i>
<i>through my entire life.</i>

10:41.633 --> 10:43.733
You need some skin work,
don't ya, huh?

10:43.733 --> 10:46.467
<i>Growing up, my mom always said,</i>

10:46.467 --> 10:49.333
<i>"Don't buy a dog.</i>
<i>Let's save a dog."</i>

10:49.333 --> 10:51.600
<i>I remember when I really wanted</i>
<i>a Dalmatian.</i>

10:51.600 --> 10:54.000
<i>Mom said, "There's always people</i>
<i>for those,</i>

10:54.000 --> 10:57.000
<i>"but there's not people to take</i>
<i>the animals from shelters</i>

10:57.000 --> 10:58.733
<i>where so many</i>
<i>will be euthanized,"</i>

10:58.733 --> 11:01.267
<i>and that's where we went.</i>

11:01.267 --> 11:03.633
<i>I'd always pick the one</i>
<i>with the saddest eyes.</i>

11:03.633 --> 11:07.467
They were wormy,
they were skinny...

11:07.467 --> 11:10.500
and something about the eyes
is what always sold 'em on me.

11:10.500 --> 11:12.500
<i>They'd look at me</i>
<i>in some sort of way</i>

11:12.500 --> 11:14.333
<i>and that's the one</i>
<i>I'd have to have.</i>

11:14.333 --> 11:16.467
This is Lily.
She's super sweet.

11:16.467 --> 11:18.700
I mean, super,
super sweet.

11:18.700 --> 11:21.000
I mean,
the problem we run into sometimes

11:21.000 --> 11:23.500
is when so many look
just the same.

11:23.500 --> 11:26.333
They're nondescript breeds
of brown and black,

11:26.333 --> 11:29.467
and it's hard to get people
to feel enticed by them.

11:29.467 --> 11:32.000
- It is. You're absolutely right.
- That's the hard part.

11:32.000 --> 11:33.333
I think she's heartworm-positive,

11:33.333 --> 11:35.700
but I'm not positive
about that.

11:35.700 --> 11:36.633
- Says it up there.
- Low positive.

11:36.633 --> 11:38.200
Heartworm positive!

11:38.200 --> 11:41.000
Heartworms actually live in the heart of a dog.

11:41.000 --> 11:43.167
They're transmitted
by mosquitoes.

11:43.167 --> 11:45.500
But people don't want
heartworm-positive dogs

11:45.500 --> 11:47.633
because they're expensive
to treat.

11:47.633 --> 11:50.233
We do 30 days of doxycycline.

11:50.233 --> 11:52.667
Then they have to stay
totally quiet for 30 days

11:52.667 --> 11:56.033
because when they get excited,
the dog can have a heart attack.

11:56.033 --> 11:58.600
The next 30 days,
they get two more injections,

11:58.600 --> 12:01.000
and then we keep 'em quiet
for another 30 days.

12:01.000 --> 12:02.333
But, you know,

12:02.333 --> 12:05.167
a heartworm preventative,
it's such a simple thing.

12:05.167 --> 12:07.033
I mean, one pill a month,

12:07.033 --> 12:09.000
your dog will not have
heartworm disease.

12:09.000 --> 12:11.733
Look at her face,
just how she looks you in the eyes.

12:11.733 --> 12:14.500
Look at her.
Like, she's staring at you right now just like...

12:14.500 --> 12:16.433
Putting her nose
right on the glass.

12:16.433 --> 12:19.433
Oh, they know how to pull
at your heartstrings.

12:19.433 --> 12:21.533
Lily, I wanna go home, huh?
Get you treated for--

12:21.533 --> 12:25.267
Oh, yes, you do. Get you treated for heartworms, huh?
- It's a deal.

12:25.267 --> 12:27.367
You wanna shake
on the deal?

12:27.367 --> 12:30.067
<i>I think Danny and I both were born</i>

12:30.067 --> 12:32.367
<i>with a true compassion</i>
<i>for animals.</i>

12:32.367 --> 12:34.433
<i>When I was a little kid,</i>

12:34.433 --> 12:36.133
<i>even though I wanted</i>
<i>to go fishing,</i>

12:36.133 --> 12:37.700
I never wanted
to put the worm on the hook

12:37.700 --> 12:39.467
'cause I felt sorry
for the worm

12:39.467 --> 12:41.667
getting the hook, you know,
zigzagged through it.

12:41.667 --> 12:45.733
<i>I was saving animals as far back as I can remember.</i>

12:45.733 --> 12:48.467
<i>When I walked home from school,</i>
<i>kind of the bigger,</i>

12:48.467 --> 12:51.033
<i>gruffer guys that were</i>
<i>a little scary to me,</i>

12:51.033 --> 12:52.700
sometimes they'd catch a turtle

12:52.700 --> 12:55.567
and then they'd just knife
its head off just for fun.

12:55.567 --> 12:57.367
<i>And even though I was</i>
<i>sort of scared of the guys,</i>

12:57.367 --> 12:59.600
<i>I'd make deals with them</i>
<i>and give them whatever I had</i>

12:59.600 --> 13:02.400
<i>to take the turtle</i>
<i>so they didn't kill it.</i>

13:02.400 --> 13:06.100
<i>I used to rescue baby robins that fell out of trees.</i>

13:06.100 --> 13:08.167
<i>We used to nurture 'em back</i>
<i>and then try to put 'em</i>

13:08.167 --> 13:10.033
<i>on our finger</i>
<i>and teach 'em how to fly.</i>

13:10.033 --> 13:14.433
<i>And horses and frogs and mice,</i>
<i>turtles in the road.</i>

13:14.433 --> 13:17.033
I mean, there-- if I see
a turtle crossing a road,

13:17.033 --> 13:19.500
you know, everybody better stop,
'cause I get out of the car

13:19.500 --> 13:21.133
and I help the turtle
cross the road.

13:21.133 --> 13:23.400
I had a rooster we got
from the Tote-Em-In Zoo

13:23.400 --> 13:25.533
because he was
in the lion's cage

13:25.533 --> 13:28.367
and the lion had
already broken his wing.

13:28.367 --> 13:30.600
And I pitched such a fit
that they ended up

13:30.600 --> 13:34.233
getting the rooster with a net
and bringing him out of the cage

13:34.233 --> 13:37.500
and then I took him
and, uh, helped heal him.

13:37.500 --> 13:39.333
So...

13:39.333 --> 13:43.267
♪♪

13:58.100 --> 13:59.700
Go, sweetie.

13:59.700 --> 14:02.033
Whew!
Let's go on in.

14:04.033 --> 14:07.633
All right, gang, meet Lily.
Hi, Lily.

14:07.633 --> 14:09.233
Lily, you're gonna get
a nice bath

14:09.233 --> 14:12.367
and get nice and clean
for us, okay?

14:12.367 --> 14:16.567
♪♪

14:16.567 --> 14:19.467
All right, sorry about that.

14:24.600 --> 14:26.167
All right, here we go.
All right.

14:28.267 --> 14:31.333
Look at you, Apollo.
I'm so proud of you.

14:39.167 --> 14:41.467
Good boy!

14:41.467 --> 14:43.533
Think she's gonna
fall asleep on us.

14:45.533 --> 14:47.167
Lily, you wanna be
wheeled out?

14:47.167 --> 14:49.067
Is that what you want?

14:49.067 --> 14:50.300
Huh?
You wanna be wheeled out?

14:50.300 --> 14:52.067
- Or you wanna walk out?
- All right.

14:52.067 --> 14:53.633
Think we can walk out, sweetie?
Come on.

14:53.633 --> 14:56.000
There you go.

14:56.000 --> 14:57.600
We got a new
family member, guys.

14:57.600 --> 14:59.667
Back up, Busy Bee.
Come on, Lily.

14:59.667 --> 15:01.600
You'll be all right.
Okay.

15:01.600 --> 15:03.633
This is part
of your new pack.

15:03.633 --> 15:05.667
This is part
of your new family, huh?

15:05.667 --> 15:08.100
Hey! Lily, stop.

15:10.300 --> 15:12.433
Stop, Lily.

15:12.433 --> 15:14.167
Might not be going
so well.

15:14.167 --> 15:16.567
Lily.

15:19.333 --> 15:22.333
No. No.
That's a no.

15:22.333 --> 15:25.633
Hi, guys.
Hi, hi.

15:28.533 --> 15:31.033
Okay, Lily.
Okay, Lily.

15:33.467 --> 15:36.567
She'll wear the muzzle for probably just a few more minutes.

15:36.567 --> 15:39.700
It's soft rubber.
It's totally humane.

15:39.700 --> 15:42.500
They can eat, they can drink,
but the only thing is,

15:42.500 --> 15:44.500
it keeps the rest
of our pack safe

15:44.500 --> 15:46.700
until she learns
social skills.

15:46.700 --> 15:49.367
We'll just keep doing this,
you know, ten times a day,

15:49.367 --> 15:51.267
just interacting her
with the pack.

15:51.267 --> 15:54.133
In a day or two, she'll probably
be running right with the pack.

15:54.133 --> 15:55.533
Yes, you're doing good, Lily.

15:55.533 --> 15:58.167
Buster Brown likes you, yes.

15:58.167 --> 16:02.100
Blanche, what do you think, huh?
